to do under
these new rules?

28:47.025 --> 28:49.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM WHEELER, Chairman, Federal
Communications
Commission: Well, the key thing
is that it

28:49.728 --> 28:51.196 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is the consumers' information.

28:51.229 --> 28:53.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's not the network's
information.

28:53.665 --> 29:00.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the consumer now has the
choice to say
how they want that information
to be used

29:00.572 --> 29:02.140 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and if they want it to be used.

29:02.174 --> 29:05.143 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, there are really three key
things.

29:05.177 --> 29:10.716 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
One, there has to be
transparency, that the
consumers have to be told,
here's what we're

29:10.749 --> 29:12.551 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
doing with your information.

29:12.584 --> 29:14.453 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Two, they have to have choice.

29:14.486 --> 29:18.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, do you want to opt in or opt
out of this
kind of service?

29:18.523 --> 29:24.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, three, that data, when it's
stored someplace,
has to be stored securely and
consumers have

29:24.396 --> 29:26.164 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to know if there is some kind of
data breach.

29:26.198 --> 29:29.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, you have
also expanded
the definition of what is
sensitive data.

29:29.701 --> 29:34.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And some businesses have pushed
back, saying,
the browsing history, the app
usage, Internet

29:34.906 --> 29:39.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
companies like Facebook and
Google, they already
have all that, and you're
placing undue burdens

29:39.311 --> 29:42.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on companies like Verizon, AT&amp;T,
et cetera.

29:42.114 --> 29:47.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM WHEELER: But what we're
talking about
is not the fact that you may go
to a dozen

29:47.919 --> 29:51.556 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sites that each will get a
little bit of information.

29:51.590 --> 29:57.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're talking about the network
that takes
you to every site and knows
everything you're

29:57.229 --> 29:58.397 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
doing.

29:58.430 --> 29:59.898 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's the big difference.

29:59.931 --> 30:05.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You hire the network to deliver
you to those
sites.

30:05.537 --> 30:11.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You don't hire the network to
take your information
without your permission and turn
around and

30:11.677 --> 30:13.378 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
resell it.

30:13.412 --> 30:16.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, businesses
are also
saying, listen, this is part of
our marketing.

30:16.148 --> 30:20.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our -- how we actually make
money is off of
this consumer data.

30:20.452 --> 30:27.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you do this, if the FCC
does this,
what about if the consumer gets
charged more,

30:27.059 --> 30:30.462 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
almost a privacy fee, a tax, if
I want to
stay private?

30:30.495 --> 30:34.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM WHEELER: Well, let's go back
to the fact
that nothing says that they
can't use this

30:34.566 --> 30:37.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
information, just that they have
to ask permission,
OK?

30:37.669 --> 30:39.471 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So that's step one.

30:39.504 --> 30:46.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Step two is that pay for privacy
-- we don't
want privacy to become some kind
of a luxury

30:46.511 --> 30:55.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
item, but we ought to look at
that on a case-by-case
basis in terms of, how does any
policies that

30:55.687 --> 31:00.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
affect pricing, what are the
specifics of
those, rather than looking at
them on some

31:00.292 --> 31:01.960 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
kind of a broad basis.

31:01.993 --> 31:05.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But, right
now, this is
limited to kind of broadband
providers.

31:05.630 --> 31:09.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are a lot of companies now
who are more
than just a broadband provider.

31:09.634 --> 31:14.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They also own content creators,
so they do
both the distribution and the
creation.

31:14.139 --> 31:15.941 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

31:15.974 --> 31:18.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what about the fact that if
I'm with AT&amp;T,
there is also the satellite,
there is also

31:18.477 --> 31:23.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the cell phone, there is also
all kinds of
things where my data could be
stored, transmitted?

31:24.015 --> 31:25.917 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This just seems to just cover a
small sliver.

31:25.951 --> 31:34.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
TOM WHEELER: So, if your
communications company
is engaged -- has other
communications activities,

31:34.459 --> 31:36.294 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they can share the information.

31:36.328 --> 31:42.234 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
But if they have
non-communications activities,
such as their own Web site and
-- or they're

31:42.267 --> 31:48.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
taking you to other Web sites,
that information
is your information, and it's
not information

31:48.807 --> 31:52.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they have the ability to
turn around
and sell without your
permission.

31:52.410 --> 32:00.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What have you
learned now,
looking back five years ago, the
merger of

32:00.152 --> 32:03.588 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Comcast or the acquisition of
NBC by Comcast?

32:03.622 --> 32:08.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not on your desk yet, but
more likely
than not AT&amp;T is trying to buy
Time Warner,

32:08.894 --> 32:11.196 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and it's going to show up in the
FCC.

32:11.229 --> 32:13.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What have you learned in those
past five years
of what worked and what didn't
work?

32:13.899 --> 32:14.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And what would you differently?

32:14.900 --> 32:16.635 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TOM WHEELER: Well, you're right.

32:16.668 --> 32:17.769 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's not on our desk yet.

32:17.803 --> 32:19.671 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we don't know what the
parameters are.

32:19.704 --> 32:25.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so what our job is, is to
develop the
facts of the case, and to make a
decision

32:25.877 --> 32:28.079 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
based on those facts.

32:28.113 --> 32:31.716 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And I think what's more
important is to say,
five years is a long tame.

32:31.750 --> 32:37.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's look at specifically
what's happening
today, what the marketplace
looks like today.

32:37.155 --> 32:41.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And let's make a decision based
on that, if,
in fact, this ends up on our
plate.

32:41.359 --> 32:46.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, is there
something that
you can say that, you know what,
these kind

32:46.364 --> 32:51.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of restrictions didn't pan out,
or these restrictions
that are only going to be in
place until,

32:51.403 --> 32:55.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
let's say, 2018, if that's what
the structure
of that deal was, they need to
be changed

32:55.607 --> 32:57.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because the market has changed
so much already?

32:57.542 --> 33:04.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM WHEELER: Well, first, you
have to say,
what are the specific
circumstances in the

33:04.583 --> 33:07.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
item that you're looking at
right then, and
then go from there.

33:07.953 --> 33:09.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we don't have that basis
yet.

33:09.521 --> 33:11.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: OK.

33:11.323 --> 33:15.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Finally, you have had a lot come
on your plate,
reclassifying broadband as a
utility, net

33:15.093 --> 33:16.294 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
neutrality.

33:16.328 --> 33:18.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when you came in, you came
from the cable
industry.

33:18.897 --> 33:21.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And people said, well, look at
this, he's
going to give them a free pass.

33:21.433 --> 33:26.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Has being on this job changed
how you think
about these things, especially
considering

33:26.371 --> 33:27.906 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
all the public comments that you
see and hear?

33:27.939 --> 33:30.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM WHEELER: Well, that is a
really interesting
question, Hari.

33:30.175 --> 33:32.978 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think I'm always -- I'm
the same person
that I always was.

33:33.011 --> 33:40.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My career has been representing
the insurgents
against the incumbents.

33:40.185 --> 33:44.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was always for the folks who
were bringing
more competition.

33:44.155 --> 33:48.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the mantra of my term at the
FCC has been
competition, competition,
competition.

33:48.293 --> 33:56.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, Tom
Wheeler,
chairman of the FCC, thanks for
joining us.

33:56.067 --> 34:00.405 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TOM WHEELER: Thank you.

