34:19.991 --> 34:22.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whether the country is heading
in the right
direction.

34:22.327 --> 34:28.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, a conversation that
takes a much
longer view about the price, and
paradox of

34:28.066 --> 34:30.702 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the country's historical
prosperity.

34:30.735 --> 34:33.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our economics correspondent,
Paul Solman has
our look.

34:33.605 --> 34:35.941 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of his weekly series,
Making Sense.

34:35.974 --> 34:37.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TODD BUCHHOLZ, Author, "The
Price of Prosperity:
Why Rich Nations Fail and How to
Renew Them":

34:37.509 --> 34:42.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Washington, D.C., is a beautiful
city, Greek,
Roman architecture.

34:42.047 --> 34:45.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our society is based on those
empires, but
they're gone.

34:45.517 --> 34:51.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, why do we think that our
country is going
to defy all of human history?

34:51.189 --> 34:56.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Because empires,
asserts Republican
economist Todd Buchholz, are so
often forced

34:57.028 --> 34:59.531 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to pay the price of prosperity.

34:59.564 --> 35:06.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TODD BUCHHOLZ: They undermine
themselves,
and they do that by racking up
more debt,

35:06.104 --> 35:10.041 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by having fewer babies born, by
more regulation.

35:10.075 --> 35:13.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's difficult to keep up
patriotism as
time goes by.

35:13.511 --> 35:18.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: "The Price of
Prosperity" is
Buchholz's downbeat new book, a
dissonant

35:18.650 --> 35:22.320 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
contrast to its upbeat author.

35:22.354 --> 35:29.861 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Buchholz was an original
investor in the musical
mega-hit "Jersey Boys," author
of the bestselling

35:29.894 --> 35:34.799 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
"New Ideas From Dead
Economists," director
of economic policy under
President George

35:34.833 --> 35:38.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
H.W. Bush, pushing economic
growth optimistically.

35:38.737 --> 35:46.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he rails at what we have
become, a people
that want everything, but won't
pay for it

35:46.344 --> 35:52.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
themselves, and, thus, in the
first of his
symptoms of prosperity malaise,
have run up

35:52.784 --> 35:56.521 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a $19 trillion national debt.

35:56.554 --> 35:57.622 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And how exactly?

35:57.655 --> 36:00.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TODD BUCHHOLZ: Because people
will lend to
us.

36:00.692 --> 36:05.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because the U.S. is a rich
country, we don't
seem to have the need yet to
discipline ourselves.

36:05.897 --> 36:10.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But in the future,
there will
be fewer Americans to cough up
the taxes to

36:10.669 --> 36:16.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pay the debt, our fertility
having fallen
below the replacement rate for
the first time

36:16.841 --> 36:18.043 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in our history.

36:18.076 --> 36:21.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Low fertility is Buchholz's
symptom number
two.

36:21.846 --> 36:24.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TODD BUCHHOLZ: This was a
hospital.

36:24.315 --> 36:25.683 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is where my kids were born.

36:25.717 --> 36:30.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lots of D.C. kids were born
here, but it's
not a hospital anymore.

36:30.588 --> 36:32.323 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's condos.

36:32.357 --> 36:35.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, throughout the world,
throughout
history, when countries get
rich, they stop

36:35.293 --> 36:36.261 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
having kids.

36:36.294 --> 36:38.329 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Because Who needs
them?

36:38.363 --> 36:41.499 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TODD BUCHHOLZ: Rich countries
don't need as
many children.

36:41.533 --> 36:46.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We used to need kids to work in
the fields
as farm hands, to crawl on their
bellies into

36:46.438 --> 36:47.872 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
coal mines.

36:47.906 --> 36:50.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, kids are more like luxury
objects now.

36:50.909 --> 36:56.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, the richer we
get, the fewer
kids we have, but is that a bad
thing?

36:57.015 --> 37:00.185 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TODD BUCHHOLZ: You need somebody
to support
the retirees.

37:00.218 --> 37:02.987 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You need to pay into the pension
plans.

37:03.021 --> 37:06.925 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You need people to work at the
hospitals,
at the nursing homes.

37:06.958 --> 37:10.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you haven't produced enough
babies to do
that...

37:10.528 --> 37:16.434 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: You need
immigration, supposed
symptom number three.

37:16.468 --> 37:21.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
TODD BUCHHOLZ: It was a
tremendous advantage
for the United States for most
of the 20th

37:21.406 --> 37:23.108 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
century.

37:23.141 --> 37:26.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But if you have waves of
immigration, you
better figure out a way to turn
those immigrants

37:26.544 --> 37:31.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into red-blooded Americans, or
else you end
up splintering the society.

37:31.749 --> 37:36.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Look at today's
anti-immigrant
backlash, says Buchholz, against
those who

37:36.821 --> 37:43.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
learn very little English,
practice a different
religion, come here illegally,
like, we were

37:43.695 --> 37:48.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
told, some of these day laborers
from Mexico
and Central America.

37:48.666 --> 37:55.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They shape up at the parking lot
next to our
"NewsHour" headquarters in
Arlington, Virginia,

37:55.073 --> 37:57.408 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
hoping for the most basic work.

37:57.442 --> 38:04.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Luis Hernandez gets hired two to
three days
a week, he says, at $15 an hour
and up.

38:04.482 --> 38:06.451 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LUIS HERNANDEZ, Day Laborer:
Renovation.

38:06.484 --> 38:07.652 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Renovation.

38:07.685 --> 38:08.887 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LUIS HERNANDEZ: Renovation.

38:08.920 --> 38:11.356 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Renovation, yes, kitchen,
bathroom, the floors.

38:11.389 --> 38:16.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Hernandez sends
money back to
his family in Guatemala.

38:16.794 --> 38:22.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jose Reyes sends money back to
Honduras to
support his wife and three kids.

38:22.267 --> 38:23.468 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How much do you send back?

38:23.501 --> 38:25.537 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOSE REYES, Day Laborer: Maybe
$500 or $600.

38:25.570 --> 38:30.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TODD BUCHHOLZ: I admire these
men for working
so hard on behalf of their wives
and their

38:30.141 --> 38:31.943 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
children.

38:31.976 --> 38:35.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when they're doing the work
and then sending
the money back home, we do have
to ask, does

38:35.213 --> 38:40.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that really contribute as much
to the American
economy as if they were devoted
to actually

38:40.185 --> 38:42.120 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
being here and staying here?

38:42.153 --> 38:50.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But there are
immigrants serving
as doctors in hospitals,
professors at universities.

38:50.995 --> 38:55.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They come, they stay, they
contribute, no?

38:55.433 --> 39:00.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TODD BUCHHOLZ: It's a good thing
we have immigrant
doctors and immigrant engineers,
because if

39:00.438 --> 39:04.442 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
you or I get sick this
